I think this counter logic is an extra calculation.

It can be simply put like this:

If any one of the rule is NOT_MET, and it is not of type EXCEPTION Exists, then return NOT_MET.
If above situation never arose, then return MET or NOT_KNOWN, as shown below.

	public TaEnum&lt;EligibilityResultType&gt; calculateOverallEligibilityStatus(final SelectedLeavePlan selectedLeavePlan) {
		final List&lt;EligibilityResult&gt; eligibilityResults = selectedLeavePlan.getEligibilityResults();
		boolean notKnownEligibilityResultExists = false;

		for (final EligibilityResult result : eligibilityResults) {
			final long eligibilityResultType = result.getEligibilityResultType().getFullId();
			final boolean exceptionEligibilityRule = IEligibilityRule.MINIMUM_HOURS_WORKED_DISPLAY_VALUE.equals(result.getEligibilityCriteriaDescription());

			if (eligibilityResultType == EligibilityResultType.NOT_MET &amp;&amp; !exceptionEligibilityRule) {
				return new TaEnum&lt;EligibilityResultType&gt;(EligibilityResultType.NOT_MET);
			} // We do not expect to have any individual rule have status PLEASE_SELECT and NOT_REQUIRED
			else if (eligibilityResultType == EligibilityResultType.NOT_KNOWN &amp;&amp; !exceptionEligibilityRule) { 
				notKnownEligibilityResultExists = true;
			}
		}

		return notKnownEligibilityResultExists ? new TaEnum&lt;EligibilityResultType&gt;(EligibilityResultType.NOT_KNOWN)
		        : new TaEnum&lt;EligibilityResultType&gt;(EligibilityResultType.NOT_KNOWN);
	}


